Definitions

  • The market price of risk is the equilibrium compensation required by investors to hold all aggregate risk
    • If all risk were tradable in the stock market, \text{market price of risk} = \frac{ \text{expected stock returns} - \text{risk-free rate} }{ \text{volatility of stock returns} }
  • The business cycle is the comovement among macroeconomic variables over the 1 to 10 year âshort runâ
    • Patterns of comovement are qualitatively the same across different cycles

Main Result: Price of Risk âdrivesâ Business Cycles

  • Empirically, two new patterns
    1. Price of risk shocks essentially the same as âbusiness cycle shockâ
    2. For business cycle variables y_t,
    \mathbb{E}[y_{t+1} \mid \text{price of risk}_t] = a + b Vol[y_{t+1} \mid \text{price of risk}_t]
  • Theoretically,
    • Empirical patterns inconsistent with mainstream models
    • But consistent with a model of financial frictions

Business cycles

Causes

  • Empirically, just one shock captures 50-75% of variation of many variables
  • In models, usually a single big shock: TFP, beliefs, confidence, etc.
  • Common propagation can look like a single shock

Why we care

  • Causes determine whether fluctuations are inefficient
  • Crucial for welfare and policy

The combination of expansions and recessions, the ebb and flow of economic activity, is called the business cycle. In many ways, the term âbusiness cycleâ is misleading. âCycleâ seems to imply that there is some regularity in the timing and duration of upswings and downswings in economic activity. Most economists, however, do not think there is, better to say âshort-run economic fluctuationsâ

Empirical Framework: Vector Autoregression (VAR)

Structural VAR(p) with k variables in vector y_t, B_0 y_t = B_1 y_{t-1} + . . . + B_p y_{t-p} + w_t where structural shocks w_t are white noise

Estimate reduced-form coefficients A_i and residuals u_t y_t = \underbrace{B_0^{-1}B_1}_{A_1} y_{t-1} + \dots + \underbrace{B_0^{-1}B_p}_{A_p} y_{t-p} + \underbrace{B_0^{-1}w_t}_{u_t}

VAR Specification is Standard

  • 1962 Q1 to 2017 Q1 with p=2 lags
  • k=10 macro variables: unemployment, interest, inflation, output, investment, consumption, hours worked, labor share, TFP, productivity
  • Or, k=11 with price of risk
    • Use âvolatility financial conditions indexâ

Volatility Financial Conditions Index (VFCI)

  • VFCI is the volatility of consumption spanned by financial assets
  • VFCI is a linear combination of stock returns, Treasury term and liquidity spreads, corporate credit and default spreads
  • Measures price of risk of representative agent in large class of models
  • Can be interpreted as tightness in financial conditions

Usual Identification Problem

  • Compare VAR in structural and reduced form \begin{align*} B_0 y_t &= B_1 y_{t-1} + . . . + B_p y_{t-p} + w_t \\ y_t &= \underbrace{B_0^{-1}B_1}_{A_1} y_{t-1} + \dots + \underbrace{B_0^{-1}B_p}_{A_p} y_{t-p} + \underbrace{B_0^{-1}w_t}_{u_t} \end{align*}
  • Structural shocks w_t related to reduced-form residuals u_t by w_t = B_0 u_t but B_0 not identified

A Main Business Cycle Shock

  • Identify a âmain business-cycleâ shock w_t^{(\text{MBC})} as in Angeletos, Collard, and Dellas (2020)
    1. Pick a target variable (e.g., unemployment)
    2. Find linear combination of residuals w_t^{(\text{MBC})} = b^T u_t that maximizes contribution of MBC shock to the volatility of target variable over business-cycle frequencies

Same Business Cycle Shock for Different Targets

  • MBC shock explains 50-75% of volatility of unemployment, investment, output, hours worked
  • Targeting unemployment, output, hours worked, consumption, or investment identifies same shock
  • Shock looks like demand shock without inflation
  • Angeletos, Collard, and Dellas (2020) propose a âconfidenceâ shock (higher-order belief shocks) as explanation

Price of Risk Shocks

  • We construct three price of risk shocks
    1. Max-share: same as MBC shock but target price of risk
    2. Timing: only shock that affects price of risk contemporaneously
    3. Heteroskedasticity: shock to the volatility of consumption within the VAR
  • All three look essentially the same as main business cycle shock

Estimation of Volatility of Consumption

  • Assume conditional volatility of consumption residuals is linear in VAR variables
  • Two-step estimation
    • Estimate VAR and define \sigma_t := \hat{u}_t^{(\text{cons})}
    • Run OLS regression \log \sigma_t^2 = c^T y_t + \vartheta_t
  • Use \hat{c}^T y_t

Conclusion

A New Business Cycle Fact

We show a new feature of business cycles

  • the price of risk comoves with the mean and vol of macro varaibles during the cycle
  • not consistent with real business cycle (RBC) or New Keynesian models

Conclusion

Financial Conditions Propagate the Business Cycle

There exists a general equilibrium structural model that is consistent with

  • the price of risk comoving with the business cycle
  • the empirical mean-vol relationship of macro variables

In the model, financial sector aggregates, amplifies, and propagates disparate shocks

  • Driven by a financial friction: the value-at-risk constraint
  • Not a single shock but a story of strong propagation
